            <section class="mt-8 prose">
              <h2>What is Days of Inventory on Hand (DOH)?</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>Days of Inventory on Hand (DOH)</strong>—also called
                <em>inventory days on hand</em>,
                <em>days sales of inventory (DSI)</em>, or
                <em>days in inventory</em>—measures how many days it would take
                to sell your current inventory at the current rate of sales or
                usage.
              </p>
              <p>
                It is a core KPI for
                <strong
                  >FP&amp;A, accounting, supply chain, and operations</strong
                >
                because it links inventory levels, demand, and working capital
                into a single, easy‑to‑interpret number.
              </p>

              <h2>Days of inventory on hand formulas</h2>

              <h3>1. DOH using average inventory (most common)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{DOH} = \frac{\text{Average Inventory}}{\text{Cost of
                  Goods Sold (COGS)}} \times \text{Number of Days} \] where \[
                  \text{Average Inventory} = \frac{\text{Beginning Inventory} +
                  \text{Ending Inventory}}{2} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is the standard formula used in financial statements and
                investment analysis because it smooths out fluctuations during
                the period.
              </p>

              <h3>2. DOH using ending inventory</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Average Daily COGS} = \frac{\text{COGS}}{\text{Number
                  of Days}} \] \[ \text{DOH} = \frac{\text{Ending
                  Inventory}}{\text{Average Daily COGS}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This version focuses on the
                <strong>inventory balance at the end of the period</strong>,
                which is useful when you care about the current snapshot on the
                balance sheet.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Operational DOH using units</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{DOH} = \frac{\text{On‑hand Units}}{\text{Average
                  Daily Usage (units/day)}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is the most intuitive formula for
                <strong>SKU‑level planning</strong> and
                <strong>replenishment</strong>: it tells you how many days until
                you run out, assuming demand stays at the current average.
              </p>

              <h2>Relationship between DOH and inventory turnover</h2>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Inventory Turnover} =
                  \frac{\text{COGS}}{\text{Average Inventory}} \] \[ \text{DOH}
                  = \frac{\text{Number of Days}}{\text{Inventory Turnover}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                DOH and inventory turnover are just two ways of expressing the
                same concept:
                <strong>how quickly you sell through inventory</strong>. Higher
                turnover means lower DOH, and vice versa.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>Suppose for the last 12 months you have:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Beginning inventory: \$200,000</li>
                <li>Ending inventory: \$260,000</li>
                <li>COGS: \$1,500,000</li>
                <li>Number of days: 365</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Step 1 – Average inventory:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \text{Average Inventory} = \frac{200{,}000 + 260{,}000}{2} =
                230{,}000 \]
              </div>
              <p>Step 2 – DOH:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \text{DOH} = \frac{230{,}000}{1{,}500{,}000} \times 365
                \approx 55.9 \text{ days} \]
              </div>
              <p>
                Interpretation: at your current sales rate, your average
                inventory covers about <strong>56 days of demand</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>How to interpret DOH</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>High DOH</strong> (many days of stock): more working
                  capital tied up, higher carrying costs, but lower stockout
                  risk.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Low DOH</strong> (few days of stock): lean inventory
                  and better cash efficiency, but higher risk of stockouts and
                  expediting costs if demand spikes or suppliers are late.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                There is no universal “good” DOH. Instead, compare your value
                against:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Your own history (is DOH trending up or down?).</li>
                <li>Targets from your S&amp;OP / inventory policy.</li>
                <li>Industry benchmarks and peer companies.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Practical tips to improve DOH</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Improve demand forecasting</strong> to reduce safety
                  stock without hurting service.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Shorten lead times</strong> with suppliers or
                  logistics improvements.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rationalize SKUs</strong> and phase out slow‑moving
                  items.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Align purchasing with sales</strong> using S&amp;OP
                  and rolling forecasts.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Segment inventory</strong> (ABC analysis) and set
                  different DOH targets by segment.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
