                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Days of Inventory on Hand (DOH) measures how many days your
                    current inventory would last at the current rate of sales or
                    usage. It is a key inventory KPI also known as inventory
                    days on hand, days sales of inventory (DSI), or days in
                    inventory.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the formula for DOH?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The most common formula is:
                    <br />
                    DOH = (Average Inventory ÷ COGS) × Number of Days.
                    <br />
                    For operational planning you can also use: DOH = On‑hand
                    Units ÷ Average Daily Usage.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is a higher or lower DOH better?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    In general, a lower DOH is better because it means faster
                    inventory turns and less capital tied up. But if DOH is too
                    low, you risk stockouts and lost sales. The optimal DOH
                    balances service level, lead times, and working capital
                    goals.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How often should I calculate DOH?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Many companies track DOH monthly or weekly at the total
                    company and category level, and daily or weekly at the SKU
                    level for critical items. The more volatile your demand and
                    lead times, the more frequently you should review DOH.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I use sales instead of COGS?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For strict accounting and financial analysis, DOH should be
                    based on
                    <strong>COGS</strong>, because inventory is recorded at
                    cost. For quick operational approximations, some teams use
                    sales, but you should be consistent and understand that this
                    mixes cost and price effects.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
